<section class="section" id="career"><div class="container"><div class="grid grid--2"><div><span class="eyebrow">Career Advancement Track</span><h2>Professional growth aligned with public purpose</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>The Career Advancement Track helps national and international graduates pursue field-aligned public-interest appointments with qualified host organizations, research institutes, universities, and mission-driven institutions.</p><p>It supports fellowship identity, host affiliation, project definition, public-interest contribution, and mission alignment.</p></div><div class="card"><div class="card__icon"><LegacyIcon name="map-signs" /></div><h3>Designed for alignment</h3><ul class="check-list"><li>Academic or professional field alignment</li><li>Defined public-benefit contribution</li><li>Qualified Host Institution affiliation</li><li>Clear project and mission scope</li><li>Membership in the Fellowship Society</li></ul></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section section--blue" id="international"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">International Graduate Fellows</span><h2>Global knowledge in service to American institutions</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>International Graduate Fellows are selected for academic achievement, field alignment, service orientation, and commitment to public-interest work. Through qualified hosts, they may contribute to research, civic projects, science, education, environmental work, humanitarian missions, and other areas of public consequence.</p></div><a class="button button--gold" href="apply.html">Apply</a></div></section>
<section class="section" id="national-capacity"><div class="container"><div class="grid grid--2"><div class="card"><div class="card__icon"><LegacyIcon name="shield" /></div><h3>Areas of contribution</h3><p>Research, infrastructure, cybersecurity, engineering, emergency management, scientific capacity, public systems, and other fields of national importance.</p></div><div><span class="eyebrow">National Capacity Fellows</span><h2>Expertise for institutional strength</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>This fellowship recognizes professionals who want to contribute their expertise to missions larger than themselves. It exists to mobilize service-minded capability for public-interest missions—not to staff companies.</p></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section section--mist" id="appointments"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Fellowship Pathways</span><h2>Ways Fellows contribute</h2><div class="rule"></div></div><div class="grid grid--3"><article class="card"><h3>Research Affiliations</h3><p>Inquiry, analysis, scientific work, public-benefit research, and knowledge translation.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>NGO Assignments</h3><p>Structured contribution to humanitarian, environmental, educational, and civic organizations.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Civic Innovation Projects</h3><p>Design, technology, policy, and community work focused on public needs.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Advisory Fellowships</h3><p>Strategic counsel and subject-matter expertise for major missions.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Graduate Appointments</h3><p>Field-aligned public-interest work tied to academic and professional development.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Mission Fellowships</h3><p>Defined service around a Society mission and a Host Institution’s work.</p></article></div><div class="actions"><a class="button button--navy" href="fellows.html">Review Fellow Criteria</a><a class="button" href="apply.html">Apply</a></div></div></section>
<section class="section"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Choosing a pathway</span><h2>Program fit follows the work</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Applicants do not need to force a complex record into a single label. The strongest pathway is the one that best explains the field, mission, level of responsibility, and institutional setting of the proposed contribution.</p></div><div class="grid grid--3"><article class="card"><h3>Start with capability</h3><p>Identify the knowledge, craft, leadership, research practice, or lived professional experience you can apply with confidence.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Name the mission</h3><p>Connect that capability to a public-interest question you understand well enough to approach with humility and discipline.</p></article><article class="card"><h3>Define the setting</h3><p>Consider the host, collaborators, supervision, timeframe, and access required for the work to be responsible and useful.</p></article></div></div></section>
<section class="section section--navy"><div class="container"><div class="grid grid--2"><div><span class="eyebrow">What varies</span><h2>Appointments are not one-size-fits-all</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Scope, duration, cadence, location, support, and outputs may differ by program and host. Those terms are made explicit for an individual appointment rather than implied by the fellowship name alone.</p></div><div><span class="eyebrow">What remains constant</span><h2>A shared standard across programs</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Every pathway joins merit to public purpose, expects responsible conduct, and asks the Fellow to produce work that a mission-driven institution or community can genuinely use.</p></div></div></div></section>
</main>

</BaseLayout>
